text: Did anybody get a good explanation from Dr Race about why the answer to the imputation question on the exam was a, b, d?  Otherwise I'll ask her.
<@U1KRNTXL5>, which one did you have the question about?

I meant a, b, or d. I got her explanation for d - the rule is that you use the mode, so it's true. I argued that the split might be close to half and half, in which case it would make more sense to impute values proportionally, but she said no, empirical studies say the mode has a better chance of being correct.
It's not c, because you shouldn't impute temperatures values at the month level, given how rapidly they change.
<@U1P8QBBD1> OK - meaning you'd be missing seasonal change?  I guess that makes sense.  Yeah I picked a,b,c rather than a,b,d <@U1KT2JJE8> thanks, I missed d by the same reasoning
The reason why I didn't pick d is because she used the word assume, I thought we never made assumptions it was always it depends
<@U1KRNTXL5> pretty much. She told me it’s changes too much to use such a large interval to approximate it. I’m guessing it would have been okay for hourly and maybe daily intervals.
